        <tr> 
          <td><textarea name="textarea" cols="40" rows="30" readonly>Image 372

Section of the rood screen in St Andrew's Church, Westhall, Suffolk, showing the Transfiguration of Christ. The first three figures, from left to right, represent Moses, bearing the tablets of the law, Christ, and Elijah. At the Transfiguration the Gospels recount that Christ's 'face shone like the sun and his garments were white as snow'. In painting of this period he is usually shown standing on a hillock, representing Mount Tabor. Here the landscape is a grassy bank with flowers. In the fourth panel is an image of St Anthony Abbot, known as the father of monasticisim who is accompanied by his pig wearing a bell round its throat.

In depicting the Transfiguration, this Suffolk screen painting is unique and probably responds to the introduction of the feast of the Transfiguration (Pfaff 1970). The screen was paid for, c.1500, by a group of well-to-do parishioners, some of whose names are still legible in the inscription along the top of the panel which requests prayers for their souls.

Munro Cautley 1937, p.364</textarea></td>
